{"chunk_id": "6ad1fda1-f1e7-494c-861b-dd2dcdcd540e", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 56, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "to build proteins. Proteins perform a wide range of functions and also provide energy (4 Kcal/g). Protein requirements vary with age, physiological status and stress. More proteins are required by growing infants and children, pregnant women and individuals during infections and illness or stress. Animal foods like milk, meat, fish and eggs and plant foods such as pulses and legumes are rich sources of proteins. Animal proteins are of high quality as they provide all the essential amino acids in right proportions, while plant or vegetable proteins are not of the same quality because of their low content of some of the essential amino acids. However, a combination of cereals, millets and pulses provides most of the amino acids, which complement each other to provide better quality proteins.", "embedding": [-0.02993955835700035, -0.055476605892181396, 0.03464839607477188, 0.03275349363684654, 0.01314194779843092, 0.0803312212228775, 0.020197633653879166, 0.042175665497779846, 0.03557039797306061, -0.010761366225779057, 0.02844165451824665, 0.0007816758006811142, -0.058725737035274506, -0.05075553059577942, 0.0724792331457138, -0.001502895844168961, 0.10617251694202423, 0.03606485575437546, -0.08874673396348953, -0.09429894387722015, 0.025242939591407776, -0.07220038771629333, -0.028869951143860817, -0.07143723219633102, 0.030095921829342842, -0.022425690665841103, -0.03814465552568436, -0.0931440070271492, 0.002920758444815874, -0.003069894155487418, 0.03604011610150337, -0.07587874680757523, 0.02345145121216774, -0.025039196014404297, -0.018129298463463783, 0.09513209760189056, 0.05190490558743477, -0.12339381128549576, -0.014243590645492077, -0.04381125047802925, 0.0016074067680165172, 0.02193952351808